"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s10",
"title":{
"__html":"Pleural Effusion"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"22e753",
"children":[
"Pleural Effusion"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s10_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"11da0c",
"children":[
"Most pleural effusions in the United States are the result of ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"heart failure",
"children":[
"HF"
]
},
","
]
},
" pneumonia, or malignancy. A thoracentesis is indicated for any new unexplained effusion. Observation and therapy without thoracentesis is reasonable in the setting of known HF, small parapneumonic effusions, or following ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"coronary artery bypass graft",
"children":[
"CABG"
]
},
" surgery."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s10_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"43a9e6",
"children":[
"Point-of-care ultrasonography can identify small effusions and determine if they are free-flowing or loculated and should be used to guide thoracentesis. Pleural fluid is characterized as transudative or exudative."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_pm_s10_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"81f2a5",
"children":[
"An effusion is considered an exudate if any one of the above criteria is met. Criteria are sensitive but not specific. Treatment (diuretics for HF), a dual diagnosis (HF and a concomitant parapneumonic effusion), or some specific diagnoses (e.g., chylothorax) can result in discordant exudates (an exudate by either the protein or ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"lactate dehydrogenase",
"children":[
"LDH"
]
},
" criterion but a transudate by the other criteria). A common cause of discordant findings is diuretic use. In the setting of ongoing diuresis, if the serum to pleural fluid albumin gradient is >1.2 g/dL, the fluid is most likely a transudate."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_pm_s10_inline_t2"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"10bdff",
"children":[
"Pleural fluid cell counts and chemistries can further narrow the differential diagnosis."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"3",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_pm_s10_inline_t3"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"80cd32",
"children":[
"Other key points:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"b7ad0c",
"children":[
"Pleural fluid adenosine deaminase is elevated in most ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"tuberculosis",
"children":[
"TB"
]
},
" effusions."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"bdf905",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Pleural biopsy is most likely to yield a positive TB culture."
]
},
" "
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"aaebac",
"children":[
"The yield for positive malignant cytology is maximized after two samples."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"8779b3",
"children":[
"Thoracoscopy should be performed for an undiagnosed exudative effusion (two negative cytology examinations) when malignancy is suspected."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s10_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"81ccf3",
"children":[
"Parapneumonic pleural effusion requires chest tube drainage if Gram stain or culture is positive, when the pH is <7.2, or if it appears loculated on imaging."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f57988",
"children":[
"Anaerobes are cultured in up to 72% of empyemas; empiric antibiotic therapy should include anaerobic coverage."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a347b3",
"children":[
"For patients with malignant effusions, indwelling pleural catheters provide symptom relief, and up to 70% of patients achieve spontaneous obliteration of the pleural space (pleurodesis) after 6 weeks. Chemical pleurodesis with talc has a 90% success rate."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"4",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_pm_f06"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"93adf4",
"children":[
"Always obtain thoracentesis for moderate to large effusions associated with pneumonia."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"9a2398",
"children":[
"Pleural effusions associated with nephrotic syndrome are common, but ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"pulmonary embolism",
"children":[
"PE"
]
},
" should be excluded in such patients because PE and renal vein thrombosis often occur in patients with nephrotic syndrome."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"dc0db8",
"children":[
"Consider pulmonary ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"lymphangioleiomyomatosis",
"children":[
"LAM"
]
},
" when chylothorax is diagnosed in a premenopausal woman."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s10_4",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"3c894c",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 65-year-old woman has a 2-week history of shortness of breath. A chest x-ray shows a large right-sided pleural effusion. Serum LDH is 190 U/L, and total protein is 6.0 g/dL. On thoracentesis, pleural fluid protein is 2.8 g/dL and pleural fluid LDH is 110 U/L."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0189bb",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose a transudative pleural effusion."
]
}
]
}
]
},
